{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522046"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:40:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:40:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13793"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13793"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.66,0.21,0.08,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70183"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6411"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13793"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55646"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1095"},{"type":"tags","id":"1818"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12625"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12661"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19814"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22999"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70183"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a two-week history of painful red nodules on both shins. She reports feeling fatigued and has developed intermittent abdominal discomfort and diarrhoea over the past month. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 72/min, blood pressure 118/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. There are tender, erythematous nodules on both shins (Image). Abdominal examination reveals mild tenderness in the right lower quadrant. A chest X-ray is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Streptococcal infection","Crohn\u0027s disease","Ulcerative colitis","Sarcoidosis","Tuberculosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely underlying cause for this patient\u0027s presentation is \u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E. The combination of erythema nodosum (painful red nodules on the shins), fatigue, and right lower quadrant abdominal pain with diarrhoea is highly suggestive of Crohn\u0027s disease. Erythema nodosum occurs in 4-15% of patients with Crohn\u0027s disease and can sometimes precede the onset of significant gastrointestinal symptoms by weeks to months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlcerative colitis\u003C/strong\u003E can also present with erythema nodosum, but it is less common (1-2% of cases) than in Crohn\u0027s disease. Additionally, the right-sided abdominal pain is more suggestive of Crohn\u0027s disease, as ulcerative colitis typically causes left-sided or diffuse abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcal infection\u003C/strong\u003E can cause erythema nodosum, but it typically presents with a sore throat and fever, which are not present in this case. Additionally, the gastrointestinal symptoms are not consistent with streptococcal infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with erythema nodosum and fatigue. However, the gastrointestinal symptoms and the absence of respiratory symptoms or hilar lymphadenopathy on chest X-ray make sarcoidosis less likely than inflammatory bowel disease in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with erythema nodosum and gastrointestinal symptoms. However, the acute onset and the lack of constitutional symptoms such as night sweats or weight loss make tuberculosis less likely than Crohn\u0027s disease in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of Crohn\u0027s disease would need to be confirmed with further investigations including inflammatory markers, faecal calprotectin, and ultimately colonoscopy with biopsies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erythema nodosum occurs in 4-15% of Crohn\u0027s disease patients but only 1-2% of ulcerative colitis patients.","Right lower quadrant pain and diarrhoea are more suggestive of Crohn\u0027s disease than ulcerative colitis.","Extra-intestinal manifestations of inflammatory bowel disease can precede gastrointestinal symptoms by weeks to months."],"references":["Perez-Garza DM, Chavez-Alvarez S, Ocampo-Candiani J, et al. Erythema Nodosum: A\u00a0Practical Approach and\u00a0Diagnostic Algorithm. Am J Clin Derm 2021: 22:367\u201378. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33683567/","Faulkes RE. Upper limb erythema nodosum: the first presentation of Crohn\u0027s disease. Clin Case Rep. 2014 Oct;2(5):183-5. doi: 10.1002/ccr3.87. Epub 2014 Jun 30. PMID: 25614807; PMCID: PMC4302621."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13793"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20735"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20735"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/st